{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 13:43:28.609349", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health assessment\\n\\nSummary\\n- Overall IP connectivity across the topology is healthy: ICMP probes between hosts and servers show 0% loss and reasonable RTTs.\\n- The central DNS server (dns_server, 10.200.0.2) is not answering DNS queries on UDP/TCP port 53. Clients attempting fresh DNS lookups to 10.200.0.2 see \"connection refused\".\\n- HTTP services (the load balancer at 10.200.0.7 and backend web servers in 10.200.0.0/24) are reachable by IP and return valid HTTP responses.\\n- Resulting condition: name resolution for the local zone is failing for clients that must query the central DNS; some clients appear to have cached/earlier-resolved names, producing inconsistent behavior.\\n\\nEvidence and relevant outputs\\n1) Reachability (summary)\\n- Bulk ping tests show the hosts, DHCP server, load balancer and web servers are reachable with 0% packet loss. (The reachability tool returned many successful ping entries, with low RTTs and no loss.)\\n\\n2) DNS failures observed from a client\\n- From host_1_1_1_1, attempts to resolve web99.local failed:\\n  - nslookup/host reported: \"communications error to 10.200.0.2#53: connection refused\" and \"no servers could be reached\".\\n- This indicates the client can reach 10.200.0.2 by IP (it attempted the TCP/UDP DNS exchange) but the DNS service refused the connection.\\n\\n3) DNS server process / socket status (dns_server = 10.200.0.2)\\n- netstat / ss output (listening sockets): shows a listener only on 127.0.0.11:39475 (local loopback), no listener on 0.0.0.0:53 or 10.200.0.2:53.\\n- systemctl status:\\n  - bind9.service — Loaded but Active: inactive (dead)\\n  - named.service — Loaded and Enabled but Active: inactive (dead)\\n- Interface and routing:\\n  - eth0: inet 10.200.0.2/24 up; default via 10.200.0.1 (networking and IP address assignment look fine).\\n\\n4) Application-level service reachability (HTTP)\\n- From host_1_1_1_1:\\n  - curl http://10.200.0.7 (load_balancer) succeeded with normal transfer times (start transfer ~0.23–0.33s, total ~1.03–1.13s).\\n  - curl http://web99.local ran earlier and returned near-instant times (namelookup:0.000000 total: ~0.005s), but subsequent explicit DNS queries to 10.200.0.2 failed. This points to cached resolution on the client for web99.local (or earlier local resolution), rather than successful live resolution from dns_server.\\n\\nAnomalies / abnormal behavior\\n- The primary abnormality is the DNS daemon on dns_server not running/listening on port 53:\\n  - Port 53 is refusing connections; systemctl shows bind/named inactive.\\n  - netstat/ss does not show DNS listening on the server\\'s external interface.\\n- Inconsistent name-resolution behavior at clients:\\n  - Some tools (curl) returned immediate responses when asked for web99.local (likely because the client already had the name->IP mapping cached), while fresh DNS lookups to the authoritative DNS at 10.200.0.2 are refused. This creates intermittent/appearingly inconsistent name resolution across clients/time.\\n- No indication (from the data collected) of packet loss, routing disconnects, or OSPF advertisement problems; IP-level forwarding and services reachable by IP address appear fine.\\n\\nLocalization — faulty device(s)\\n- dns_server (10.200.0.2) — the DNS service (BIND/named or equivalent) is inactive/not listening. This is the localized fault affecting name resolution.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis\\n- Root cause (as evidenced): The DNS server process is not running on dns_server, leaving UDP/TCP port 53 closed/refusing connections. The service(s) for DNS (bind9/named) are inactive. Because the DNS server is the central authority for the local zone, hosts that rely on it for name resolution cannot resolve local service names (web99.local, web0.local, etc.) unless they have cached entries.\\n- Contributing/system context evidence:\\n  - The host network config on dns_server is correct (10.200.0.2 present, routing present), so the problem is an application/service failure (DNS daemon) rather than an IP/interface or routing issue.\\n  - Other infrastructure elements (DHCP server, FRR routers, load balancer, web servers) are reachable and continuing to function at the IP level.\\n\\nImpacts observed\\n- Name resolution for the local zone fails for fresh lookups to the authoritative DNS. This will cause:\\n  - Clients unable to resolve web99.local (and other local names) -> inability to access services by name.\\n  - Intermittent/partial accessibility where clients with cached DNS entries can still contact services by name, while others cannot.\\n- Direct IP access to services (e.g., load balancer at 10.200.0.7) works; so service layer (HTTP) and routing are otherwise healthy.\\n\\nOther observations\\n- There is at least one local listener on 127.0.0.11 (an internal stub resolver or local resolver process), but it is not serving external DNS queries. This may explain why some lookups that use a local cache succeed while queries to the central server fail.\\n- The systemctl output shows both bind9 and named present; named is enabled but inactive. This could indicate a configuration/packaging inconsistency or prior manual changes — but the immediate effect is the same: DNS service inactive.\\n\\nConclusion (diagnosis)\\n- Network-level connectivity and routing are healthy across the enterprise network.\\n- The central DNS server (dns_server, 10.200.0.2) has its DNS daemon(s) inactive and is refusing DNS queries; this is the principal fault causing name resolution failures and inconsistent client behavior.\\n- No evidence found of broader routing or server reachability faults; the problem is localized to the DNS service on dns_server.\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- (upon your instruction) collect additional logs/configs from dns_server (journalctl for bind9/named, bind config files) to further explain why the DNS service is inactive, or\\n- run fresh DNS queries from other hosts to confirm scope of impact, or\\n- continue to inventory router BGP/OSPF state if you suspect routing anomalies., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='5e9d4700-dfac-4613-84c7-60b0c2001c0c'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
